              <span id="reviewTextContainer3563029887" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2791561345088682634">I have heard of this book for years but never thought to read it until now, and I am glad that I did because it was interesting, to say the least.. <br/><br/>This happens to be the sequel to her book, “Through the Narrow Gate” and centers around her nervous breakdown after leaving the convent. There were two issues that bothered me. One was her continuing to be around the nuns that had harmed her, and the second one was her Freudian therapist. At least, in time, she moved away and was no longer around the</span>
  <span id="freeText2791561345088682634" style="display:none">I have heard of this book for years but never thought to read it until now, and I am glad that I did because it was interesting, to say the least.. <br /><br />This happens to be the sequel to her book, “Through the Narrow Gate” and centers around her nervous breakdown after leaving the convent. There were two issues that bothered me. One was her continuing to be around the nuns that had harmed her, and the second one was her Freudian therapist. At least, in time, she moved away and was no longer around the nuns, and then, as for the therapist, at least she had the strength to tell him that he was wrong. He was wrong.<br /><br />After leaving and making new friends, she never felt that she fit in, but maybe that took time. The only book that I really liked of hers was “The History of God,” which I found to be an eye opener.</span>
