<div id="review_37816703" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/37816703" />
    <a title="Sonya" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1295781-sonya"><img alt="Sonya" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1603207094p2/1295781.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/37816703?book_show_action=true">Nov 15, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sonya" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sonya" href="/user/show/1295781-sonya">Sonya</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1295781-sonya?shelf=2020">2020</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer37816703" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9380481032130047402">2004 review: Karen Armstrong is a thoughtful and intelligent writer, who is unafraid to ask hard questions about theology and its practice. This would be a great book club pick.<br/><br/>2020 thoughts: <br/>In The Spiral Staircase: Karen Armstrong has just left the convent and must navigate the changed world of the 1960s. She didn&apos;t fit in as a nun and doesn&apos;t feel comfortable or happy in the outside, either. The memoir charts her journey of finding her place in the world, thinking she&apos;ll be an academic or a t</span>
  <span id="freeText9380481032130047402" style="display:none">2004 review: Karen Armstrong is a thoughtful and intelligent writer, who is unafraid to ask hard questions about theology and its practice. This would be a great book club pick.<br /><br />2020 thoughts: <br />In The Spiral Staircase: Karen Armstrong has just left the convent and must navigate the changed world of the 1960s. She didn't fit in as a nun and doesn't feel comfortable or happy in the outside, either. The memoir charts her journey of finding her place in the world, thinking she'll be an academic or a teacher and struggling in those fields, all while experiencing blackouts and exhaustion, which is written off for years as psychiatric and therefore not real. She's finally diagnosed with epilepsy and at that point she investigates various religious figures and the notion of God over centuries. Her conclusion after writing numerous books about Saint Paul, God, Islam, and more is that the worth of religion comes through acts. The memoir is highly critical of the institutions that suppress personality to the point of erasure. <br /><br />The nuns of Armstrong's world are not the well-meant and kind nuns in Rumer Godden's invention. Instead, the nuns in charge of Armstrong's life are petty bullies who belittle weaker nuns to the point of breakdown, then call them 'melodramatic.' The worst parts of organized religion are in this recollection, yet Armstrong dedicates her life toward understanding the importance to culture and human experience the desire to seek meaning beyond physical existence. The analogy of the spiral staircase, taken from Eliot's poetry, shows how Armstrong cobbles together a faith that does not depend on an institution. </span>
  <a data-text-id="9380481032130047402" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


